text:
Today I rewatched Gura's last collab with Ame month ago. She looked so calm, so detached, so... troubled, probably. Maybe there is some reason for this pause, maybe there isn't, whatever. I'm not even a proper chumbud anymore and cannot be one, so I'm probably the last man who may talk about it.

But from the bottom of my heart I wish you, Gawr Gura, the Shark of Atlantis, two simple things: be fine and be happy. Be happy, if you decided to leave streaming behind and live a calm life, be happy, if you're just busy with some stuff and going to return, soon or not. For three years your cheerful laughter, your funny shenanigans, your soothing voice was giving me happiness I haven't thought I still can feel for quite a while, so you just deserve to be happy too - on whatever path you choose to walk. I would be sad if we won't hear your voice anymore, but if that's what you need to have a peace of mind, so be it. You deserve it just as anybody else.

May your way be light and may your smile be bright, Gura, below any stars in any land. God bless you.

text: ¬†@NotTheWheel¬† She straight up said in her last stream that she has burnout. Most workplaces at least where I live are supposed to grant you quite long sick leave if you have burnout, and Gura once again mentioned in her last stream (and is obvious if you look at the Gurarium stuff and the new MV) has still been working, just more behind the scenes than streaming.
author: @HyattHyatt3179

text: ¬†@HyattHyatt3179¬† you work some place where you can take months off?
author: @NotTheWheel

text:
¬†@NotTheWheel¬† When it comes to more serious stuff like severe burnout then yes, by law you can take months off where I live. You do need to be able to prove that you suffer from burnout or whatever illness it was that you needed to take time of for though. You can also decrease your work hours due to this if you don't want to stop completely. 

While you can get fired during this period, you're not allowed to be fired due to the illness/break, and it has to be because of something else, like your work not being done properly prior to your illness. 

It also depends if it's indefinite/long term, or if it's for a few months. 

But yeah in my country you are legally allowed to take a longer period of time off due to burnout if you can give your company a doctors note proving it, and still keep your job. At least in 90% of the cases.

text: The vocal minority's main issue is not the lack of streaming, but rather their incessant need for communication. They whine and complain about not knowing when the next stream will be, as if their lives revolve around it. Instead of accepting the fact that there might not be a stream, they throw tantrums like entitled brats. And to make matters worse, they demand a detailed explanation for any breaks, as if the streamer owes them anything. They expect the streamer to cater to their every whim and provide a legitimate and reasonable justification for every little inconvenience. It's laughable how their standards for what constitutes a valid reason to be unable to stream are so skewed. They nitpick and criticize every move the streamer makes, as if they have any right to dictate how they should spend their time. Despite the fact that there are countless other streamers to watch, these individuals stubbornly cling to their "ride or die" mentality. They willingly subject themselves to constant disappointment, all because they can't handle the slightest deviation from their unrealistic expectations. If the streamer doesn't meet their standards, they should have the common sense to find someone else who does. But no, they choose to wallow in their own misery and drag others down with them. It's pathetic how they lack any emotional control and refuse to change their behavior, even when everyone else sees it as foolish and terrible.

I do commend the chumbuds that can keep being optimistic despite all this, but without any information, we're just stuck with a bunch of speculations. text:
At this point this seems the most likely possibility, she could just be severely burned out, having so many eyes and expectations placed on you when you are introverted must be very taxing. I can imagine that because I'm introverted too and have this urge to just run away from things when I'm too stressed. I manage, but everyone's different.

It may seem easy to just tweet something about the situation and at times I feel disappointed too even if I just discovered her recently. But honestly I just start to think it's just avoidant behavior, she may want to run away from it all, at least for a while, while not wanting to admit that she's running. It'd fit well with how she does promise things and wants to communicate more but she just can't seem to be able to deliver. 

Physical health is probably a factor but not the whole picture since she can collab just fine. They probably just coaxed her into doing those, if you are not the sole entertainer of the stream it's obviously much less stressful. Remember her self deprecating tweet? "Guess who remembered she's a streamer" She may be hating herself right now for not bringing herself to stream, which makes things worse of course. Imposter syndrome possibly. Which I have too, all the time.

Go rewatch the first vod of the anniversary myth relay. She seemed sedated to me, so she may have taken something to deal with the stress of not being able to skip something so important as an anniversary.

I'm not saying she 100% is not a lazy bum who just realized she can rake in the money with little effort, I have no scrying ball. But I still think this is probably not the case. I'm very glad that everywhere else she still receives positive feedback from her fans, it's only here that's problematic, so I felt I had to say something again on the matter.

Keep giving her the benefit of the doubt I say, she'll be back hopefully. Being nasty to her won't achieve a damn thing anyway. And being nasty to your fellow chumbuds won't either. I know this sucks, I hate it too, she just may not help running away from it all right now. I just hope she gets her confidence back and comes back to streaming soon, I'm having a blast with her vods in the meanwhile, also Shinkiro was top notch üòÆ

Hold the line chumbuds, lol

author: @j3omega

text: ¬†@j3omega¬† I think you're missing the main issue here, and it's Gura's lack of communication. Hololive members usually let their fans know when they're taking an extended break, because it keeps them in the loop and avoids speculation, confusion or the feeling that they're taken for granted. Most people understand that personal issues can come up and the streamer should prioritize their well being first and foremost. But Gura has been absent for over a month now and hasn't even done the courtesy of giving an update, and I think it's justified for chumbuds to be upset about that (especially if they're paying for a membership). Collabs are nice, but people are subscribed to Gura's channel to watch her content. Instead, they're seeing her appear on other streamers' channels while seemingly neglecting her own, and I can't stress enough that all this confusion and negative feedback could be avoided if she simply gave her fans an explanation for the sudden hiatus.
author: @izilladkilla

text:
@izilladkilla¬† Don't worry. I'm aware of the lack of communication. It's just not really a big deal to me like it seems to be for others. Mostly because I'm subscribed to multiple other channels that have similarly long and inconsistent upload schedules. While I understand the frustration at the lack of communication, most people are going about voicing that frustration in a way that I don't sympathize with. 

To me, it's as simple as this. If members don't like her lack of uploads and communication, they should cancel their membership until Gura gets back to an upload schedule that's acceptable to them. For those that aren't members, unsubscribe if you feel the need. Otherwise, find other content on YouTube to enjoy until Gura streams again.

What they shouldn't do and what's all too common for people in the comments is people just sitting around complaining nonstop. If they're upset that there's no content, there's always the collab streams I mentioned in my original comment, which was my intention with that post, but otherwise, complaining feels pointless. Neither Gura or anyone else from Hololive are looking at the comments section of these videos, so many people are just screaming into the void, all while still supporting her with views, subscriptions, merch, and memberships.

If they're upset, then they should show that frustration in a way that will make a difference. Hololive are far more likely to respond to their largest vtuber's subscriber count, merch sales, and memberships dropping than they are with a bunch of upset comments. I have no problem with fans showing their disapproval of the lack of communication from Gura and Hololive by hurting them financially, but I have no sympathy for people who still choose to support them financially while constantly complaining in the comments section about them.

As for my other replies, I'm responding the way I am just because it's clear that they're anti's who are looking for attention and to fish for a negative reaction. Being positive and dismissive feels like the best way to respond imo ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

text:
Hi.

I suppose it doesn't hurt to add my views onto this. I am not a Gura fan in the strict sense, but I think I can understand the situation. 

The lecturing here over people being incels or being beggars is already stupid and pointless. Nobody says it all to add something meaningful to the whole discussion.

Regarding Gura's situation, it's true, the lack of streams and content certainly is something that can't be overlooked. Fans might be worrying about everything with her, leading to unnecessary speculation like mental health, getting tired of the fans, laziness. It would be at least fair within the reasonable framework that Gura addressed the situation properly about the streams. It's not that fans are entitled to that. It's just if she isn't enjoying the job, something she did on her own will, and at least if she isn't enjoying it, it would be reasonable to leave, graduate or else. She is not forced to compel, after all.

If she is currently busy, this complicates the situation, because VTubing implies a bit of dedication to what you're doing. Of course, I don't think people need to be compelled in all regards, but I think solving the situation is more important.

I am saying it for the sake of everyone. VTubing is for people to have fun, both the entertainers and the audience. That harmony builds the base for a healthier community.

I just hope you're doing well, Gura, if you read this.

text:
For some, if not most of us, it's not about the when, it's more about the WHY -- why she has been taking these long breaks in between activity. It's not a question out of demand, it's a question out of concern -- our worries come from mental and/or physical well-being (analogous to Haachama and her long-time absence). We ask less about our wants, but more about her needs -- she needs help if something is actually wrong. 

In other words, we want to have reasons, as reasons ease confusion. I'm not saying to pry too deep into a VTuber's personal life, especially if they are adamant about keeping their own affairs private. But there are people that care a lot for Gura, so it's not going to stop them from asking what is wrong. They want to understand, empathize, and offer advice on well-being. If we have at least the information to do so, then we can worry less and  respect more. 

It's rather a predicament that can lead to more stress. Isn't it? The unfortunate part is having too many people that care, there's those who you don't want caring as much.

text:
As someone who has consumed Vtuber content for a year or so, I have a question: Why do you still watch this? 

You could be spending your time way more wisely; with, for example, training, studying, or even watching something more interesting and informative. I don't think this type of content gives or helps you get any sort of life skill (it certainly didn't give me anything), but it definitely takes away something extremely valuable: your time. Another thing I want to ask is why would someone with a virtual uwu character who doesn't know you and perhaps doesn't even care about you make your day better? I know that we all have ups and downs, it's part of life. However, why should your mood depend on pixels on a computer screen? It shouldn't, because if you spent your time in a more meaningful way you would be able to more or less control your emotions and mood, thus making you a more accomplished and successful individual. 

Again, I am writing all of this as someone who has been in the same position as you are in. You have the choice to be someone better. I believe in you!

text:
It's genuinely amazing to think that it has now been over three years since I sat there and watched a lil shork emerge on screen for the first time, :_GuraA:ing her lil heart out:_gurapat:My life has changed so much over these three years, and it has been an absolute pleasure to grow alongside you Guwa. You are so sweet and emotionally intelligent and hard-working and funny, so kind and talented and wonderful. You are an absolute joy to be around, and I can only say: thank you so so much for spending these three years with us. I am so proud of you and so happy for you; you've achieved so much! I still remember crying when you first appeared on stage at HoloFes, knowing how much it meant to the lil shork who sat at the kitchen table and told momma shark that she would be there one day:_WuvXob:

Here's to an amazing year four! We will be with you for as long as you will have us Gwumbus, and I look forward to growing with you for another year:_Celebrate:Love you dearly Guwa; thank you for being the bestest shork everüíô:_Snuggle:Take care, and be kind to yourself - you deserve it:_gurapat:

P.S. I always say this when something like 3D comes out, but: it is always so lovely to see more of your personality come out in your movements! Whenever we get 3D or handcams or anything like that, it is just so wonderful to see more of how you move and your body language and just the delightful (slightly goofy) you:_gurapat:Also swimsuit so cuuuute~! I love the details of all the ribbon-y, pseudo-skirt-y stuff around the waist!
